BM424 workshop: infectious disease outbreak control

Morgan Feeney

17/03/2023

Scenario D

Campylobacter jejuni outbreak in Rosblane

The Rosblane Pandemic Response committee has gathered the following information for the second meeting of your group.

You should evaluate the effect(s) of the actions that you took at your last meeting and evaluate the current state of affairs in Rosblane.

You should submit 3-5 specific actions for further actions to control the pandemic, using the workshop 4 pro forma (also available on MyPlace). You should consider whether you want to continue any of the public health measures you implemented at your previous meeting, or whether you want to stop them; and also whether there are any new, additional actions you would like to take. Submit the pro forma by noon on Friday March 24th, via the submission link on MyPlace.

News Coverage of the Rosblane Campylobacter outbreak

Rosblane News
Rosblane says farewell to pandemic’s youngest victim
by S.R. O’Brien 10/03/2023

The Campylobacter jejuni pandemic ravaging Rosblane has claimed yet another victim. There have been 43 deaths in the pandemic so far, but perhaps the most tragic loss is Freya Taylor - at only 2, the youngest victim that the pandemic has claimed.

Freya Taylor liked horses and flowers. Friends and family say that she was always a treasure.

Freya is survived by her parents and grandparents, and by her siblings Carter, David, and Milo.

The funeral service will be held Saturday at Trinity Church.

Rosblane Evening News
Rosblane says farewell to local legend
by Jane Charles 13/03/2023

The Campylobacter jejuni pandemic ravaging Rosblane has claimed yet another victim. Ronnie Watson, local artist and star, sadly passed away on Monday.

Ronnie was perhaps best known for his 2005 work A Fool’s Errand , but fans say that the rest of his work was equally as memorable.

Ronnie is survived by his husband, and by his siblings Hester and Winifred.

The funeral service will be held Friday at St. Judes.

Rosblane Evening News
Rosblane pandemic council making great strides
by Norman Moore 06/03/2023

Citizens of Rosblane should be grateful that the city’s Pandemic Response Council, swiftly convened when a new pandemic began to hit Rosblane, has been so effective. While the initial death toll from the pandemic appeared to be quite alarming, the actions taken by the PRC seem to have been most effective.

Officials from the World Health Organisation have publicly praised the Rosblane PRC, saying that it is difficult to imagine a more effective public health response

There have been 8 deaths due to Campylobacter jejuni in Rosblane this week. This is an enormous decrease, and hopefully Rosblane will see the death toll continue to decrease in the coming weeks.

Rosblane Sentinel
Yet more overreach in the name of “science”
by Louisa Stein 05/03/2023

Governments across the globe have seen how successful power-grabs in the name of public health can be, following on the wave of restrictions imposed because of so-called viral diseases like COVID-19 and “mpox”. So-called scientists are fearmongering - aerosols, monkeys, “bird” flu - now they think that they can fool us into thinking that the food and water are unsafe. Citizens of Rosblane should stand strong against this terrible tyranny! No more mask mandates, no more senseless restrictions!

Our elders should not be left to die alone, left frightened and hopeless in a mandatory lockdown claimed to be “for their benefit.” Our children should not be left to struggle through “pandemic” after “pandemic” - their language and literacy skills have been left behind due to these lockdowns, and their mental health is suffering. It is time that we take back control of our lives and end this tyranny of fear-mongering and so-called science. Citizens of Rosblane, stand with me and resist this most recent attack on your freedoms and your lives.

BBC Scotland
Campylobacter jejuni pandemic in Rosblane
by Joseph Holmes 10/03/2023

Hard on the heels of the COVID-19 pandemic and a number of other health scares (monkeypox, or “mpox”, avian flu, and worries about other infectious disease outbreaks), another pandemic has hit the Scottish town of Rosblane. This time, it’s Campylobacter jejuni, a bacterium that causes a sometimes fatal illness.

There have been 43 deaths in the pandemic so far, but perhaps the most frightening aspect to this new pandemic is rumours that antibiotic-resistant Campylobacter strains have begun to emerge.

Scientists have been warning about the antibiotic resistance crisis for years, saying that careless use of antibiotics could mean that these precious medicines will no longer be available to us in the future. The pandemic response council in Rosblane have recommended that doctors not prescribe antibiotics in this particular pandemic - hoping to save these precious medicines for our future use.

Nonetheless, this pandemic in Rosblane raises key questions about the safety of the food and water we eat and drink. Will matters worsen - perhaps because of the forthcoming loosening of standards due to the loss of certain legislative protections? Are there monsters lurking in the frozen chicken section of the supermarket?
